"Cui X., Graf H.-F.","Recent land cover changes on the Tibetan Plateau: A review",2009,"Climatic Change","94","1-2",,"47","61",,,10.1007/s10584-009-9556-8,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-67349180208&partnerID=40&md5=4a8cf0d1c2ddb7d07e3d4f714b64d5aa","Department of Geography, University of Liverpool, Roxby Building, Liverpool L69 7ZT, United Kingdom; Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing, China; Centre for Atmospheric Science, University of Cambridge, Cambridge, United Kingdom","Cui, X., Department of Geography, University of Liverpool, Roxby Building, Liverpool L69 7ZT, United Kingdom, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing, China; Graf, H.-F., Centre for Atmospheric Science, University of Cambridge, Cambridge, United Kingdom","This paper reviews the land cover changes on the Tibetan Plateau during the last 50 years partly caused by natural climate change and, more importantly, influenced by human activities. Recent warming trends on the plateau directly influence the permafrost and snow melting and will impact on the local ecosystem greatly. Human activities increased rapidly on the plateau during the last half century and have significant impacts on land use. Significant land cover changes on the Tibetan Plateau include permafrost and grassland degradation, urbanization, deforestation and desertification. These changes not only impact on local climate and environment, but also have important hydrological implications for the rivers which originate from the plateau. The most noticeable disasters include the flooding at the upper reaches of Yangtze River and droughts along the middle and lower reaches of Yellow River. Future possible land cover changes under future global climate warming are important but hard to assess due to the deficits of global climate model in this topographically complex area. Integrated investigation of climate and ecosystems, including human-beings, are highly recommended for future studies. © 2009 Springer Science+Business Media B.V.",,"Global climate models; Global climate warming; Grassland degradations; Human activities; Land-cover changes; Local climates; Significant impacts; Snow-melting; Tibetan plateaux; Yangtze rivers; Yellow rivers; Deforestation; Drought; Ecosystems; Land use; Landforms; Permafrost; Rivers; Vegetation; Climate change; deforestation; desertification; drought; global warming; grassland; human activity; land cover; land degradation; permafrost; snow; urbanization; Asia; China; Eurasia; Far East; Qinghai-Xizang Plateau; Yangtze River",,,,,,"Bengtsson, L., Hagemann, S., Hodges, K.I., Can climate trends be calculated from reanalysis data? (2004) Journal of Geophysical Research D: Atmospheres, 109 (11), pp. D111111-8. , DOI 10.1029/2004JD004536; Beniston, M., Climatic change in mountain regions: A review of possible impacts (2003) Climatic Change, 59 (1-2), pp. 5-31. , DOI 10.1023/A:1024458411589; Beniston, M., Fox, D.G., The impacts of climate change on mountain regions (1996) Second Assessment Report of Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), Chapter 5, , Cambridge University Press Cambridge; Brauning, A., Mantwill, B., Summer temperature and summer monsoon history on the Tibetan plateau during the last 400 years recorded by tree rings (2004) Geophysical Research Letters, 31 (24), pp. 1-4. , DOI 10.1029/2004GL020793, L24205; Brovkin, V., Sitch, S., Von Bloh, W., Claussen, M., Bauer, E., Cramer, W., Role of land cover changes for atmospheric CO2 increase and climate change during the last 150 years (2004) Global Change Biology, 10 (8), pp. 1253-1266. , DOI 10.1111/j.1365-2486.2004.00812.x; Charney, J.G., Dynamics of deserts and droughts in the Sahel (1975) Q J R Meteorol Soc, 101, pp. 193-202; Cheng, G., Wu, T., Responses of permafrost to climate change and their environmental significance, Qinghai-Tibet Plateau (2007) Journal of Geophysical Research F: Earth Surface, 112 (2), pp. F02S0